[{"id":"/sicpjs/2.2.1","tag":"TITLE","body":"2.2.1  \n    Representing Sequences"},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p1","child":[{"body":"\n\n    One of the useful structures we can build with pairs is a \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"sequence","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":"—an ordered collection of data objects.  There\n    are, of course, many ways to represent sequences in terms of pairs.  One\n    particularly straightforward representation is illustrated in\n    figure ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.4","href":"/sicpjs/2.2.1#fig-2.4"},{"body":",\n      \n    where the sequence 1, 2, 3, 4 is represented as a chain of pairs.  The\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"head"},{"body":"\n    of each pair is the\n    corresponding item in the chain, and the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"tail"},{"body":"\n    of the pair is the next pair in the chain.  The\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"tail"},{"body":"\n    of the final pair signals the end of the\n    \n\tsequence,\n      \n    represented in box-and-pointer\n    diagrams as a diagonal line\n    \n    and in programs as\n    \n\tPython's primitive value\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"None"},{"body":".\n      \n    The entire sequence is constructed by nested\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"pair"},{"body":"\n    operations:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":1,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYA4EMCWATgBRoA0IGI11eRxiFVNLtBJAzE6zy3SQBYKAOQD2AOwCmASlnSgA","body":"pair(1, \n     pair(2, \n          pair(3, \n               pair(4, None)))) "}]},{"tag":"FIGURE","scale":"70%","src":"img_javascript/ch2-Z-G-13.svg","id":"#fig-2.4","captionHref":"/sicpjs/2.2.1#fig-2.4","captionName":"Figure 2.4 ","captionBody":[{"body":"The sequence 1, 2, 3, 4 represented as a chain of pairs.\n\t  ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p2","child":[{"body":"\n    Such a sequence of pairs, formed by nested\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"pair"},{"body":" applications,\n      \n    is called a\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"linked list","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":",\n      \n    and\n    our Python environment\n    provides a primitive called \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"llist"},{"body":"\n    to help in constructing\n    linked\n    lists.","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FOOTNOTE_REF","id":"#footnote-link-1","body":"1","href":"/sicpjs/2.2.1#footnote-1"},{"body":"\n    The above sequence could be produced by\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"llist(1, 2, 3, 4)"},{"body":".\n      \n    In general, \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":true,"eval":false,"body":"\nllist($a$$_{1}$, $a$$_{2}$, $\\ldots$, $a$$_{n}$)\n      "},{"body":"\n    is equivalent to\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":true,"eval":false,"body":"\npair($a$$_{1}$, pair($a$$_{2}$, pair($\\ldots$, pair($a$$_{n}$, None)$\\ldots$)))\n      "},{"body":"\n        Our interpreter prints pairs using a textual representation of\n\tbox-and-pointer diagrams that we call ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"box notation","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":".\n        \n\tThe result of ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"pair(1, 2)"},{"body":"\n        is printed as ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"[1, 2]"},{"body":", and\n\tthe data object in figure ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.4","href":"/sicpjs/2.2.1#fig-2.4"},{"body":" \n        is printed as \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"[1, [2, [3, [4, None]]]]"},{"body":":\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":2,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYPYDsCmA+gC4AWATtgK4DmphAZteSALwgA2HAlgM7EAKNABokogMyiALAEosAB3LdcgvETKVa9JlXIygA","body":"one_through_four = llist(1, 2, 3, 4) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":3,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYPYDsCmA+gC4AWATtgK4DmphAZteSALwgA2HAlgM7EAKNABokogMyiALAEosAB3LdcgvETKVa9JlXIygA","body":"print(one_through_four) ","output":"[1, [2, [3, [4, None]]]]"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p3","child":[{"body":"\n    We can think of \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"head"},{"body":"\n    as selecting the first item in the\n    linked list,\n    and of \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"tail"},{"body":"\n    as selecting the\n    linked-list component\n    consisting of all but the first item.  Nested\n    applications of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"head"},{"body":"\n    and\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"tail"},{"body":"\n    can be used to extract the second, third, and subsequent items in the\n    linked list.\n    The constructor \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"pair"},{"body":"\n    makes a\n    linked list\n    like the original one, but with an additional item at the\n    beginning.\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":4,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYPYDsCmA+gC4AWATtgK4DmphAZteSALwgA2HAlgM7EAKNABokogMyiALAEosAB3Ldcg0vgCGAEwF4iZSrXpMq5GTKA","body":"print(head(one_through_four)) ","output":"1"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":5,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYPYDsCmA+gC4AWATtgK4DmphAZteSALwgA2HAlgM7EAKNABokogMyiALAEosAB3Ldcg4gENuHAXiJlKtekyrkZMoA","body":"print(tail(one_through_four)) ","output":"[2, [3, [4, None]]]"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":6,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYPYDsCmA+gC4AWATtgK4DmphAZteSALwgA2HAlgM7EAKNABokogMyiALAEosAB3Ldcg0vgCGAEwHF13DgLxEylWvSZVyM60A","body":"print(head(tail(one_through_four))) ","output":"2"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":7,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYPYDsCmA+gC4AWATtgK4DmphAZteSALwgA2HAlgM7EAKNABokogMyiALAEosAB3Ldcg+QENu5IQAZReImUq16TKuRkygA","body":"print(pair(10, one_through_four)) ","output":"[10, [1, [2, [3, [4, None]]]]]"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":8,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYPYDsCmA+gC4AWATtgK4DmphAZteSALwgA2HAlgM7EAKNABokogMyiALAEosAB3Ldcg+QENu5AQFZReImUq16TKuRkygA","body":"print(pair(5, one_through_four)) ","output":"[5, [1, [2, [3, [4, None]]]]]"},{"body":"\n        The value ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"None"},{"body":", used to terminate\n\tthe chain of pairs, can be thought of as a sequence of no elements, the \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"empty linked list","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":".","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FOOTNOTE_REF","id":"#footnote-link-2","body":"2","href":"/sicpjs/2.2.1#footnote-2"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p4","child":[{"body":"\n      Box notation is sometimes difficult to read. In this book, when we want to\n      indicate the\n      linked-list nature of a data structure, we will employ the\n      alternative\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"linked-list notation","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":": Whenever possible, linked-list notation uses\n      applications\n      of ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"llist"},{"body":" whose evaluation would result in the\n      desired structure. For example, instead of the box notation\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":9,"eval":false,"output":"[1, [[2, 3], [[4, [5, None]], [6, None]]]]"},{"body":"\n      we write\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":10,"eval":false,"output":"llist(1, [2, 3], llist(4, 5), 6)"},{"body":"\n      in linked-list notation.","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FOOTNOTE_REF","id":"#footnote-link-3","body":"3","href":"/sicpjs/2.2.1#footnote-3"}]},{"tag":"SUBHEADING","id":"#h1","child":[{"body":"Linked-list\n    operations","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p5","child":[{"body":"\n    The use of pairs to represent sequences of elements as\n    linked lists\n    is accompanied\n    by conventional programming techniques for manipulating\n    linked lists\n    by\n    successively \n    \n\tusing ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"tail"},{"body":" to walk down the\n\tlinked lists.\n      \n    For example, the\n    function","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"ref"},{"body":"\n    takes as arguments a\n    linked list\n    and a number ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$n$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" and\n    returns the ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$n$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":"th item of the\n    linked list.\n    It is\n    customary to number the elements of the\n    linked list\n    beginning with 0.  The method\n    for computing\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"ref"},{"body":"\n    is the following:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"UL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\tFor ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$n=0$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":",\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"ref"},{"body":"\n\tshould return the\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"head"},{"body":"\n\tof the\n\tlinked list.","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\tOtherwise,\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"ref"},{"body":"\n\tshould return  the ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$(n-1)$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":"st item of the\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"tail"},{"body":"\n\tof the\n\tlinked list.","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":11,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIATgQBQCWALrgLYDOANCAHYCUAXBiN8bpQK5FmIUgAtcAQ2wVq9ViHKFhAXmUgADFx7btuADZ1cvfKUoTyembTqsmwgLQg0rVljoBHfhJJ0QavXrkdJSkaEwALEwAnExoAGxMiACsrhgADkTkzCEkJh5ePkwAzC5AA","body":"def ref(items, n):\n    return (head(items) if n == 0\n            else ref(tail(items), n - 1)) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":12,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIATgQBQCWALrgLYDOANCAHYCUAXBiN8bpQK5FmIUgAtcAQ2wVq9ViHKFhAXmUgADFx7btuADZ1cvfKUoTyembTqsmwgLQg0rVljoBHfhJJ0QavXrkdJSkaEwALEwAnExoAGxMiACsrhgADkTkzCEkJh5ePkwAzC5AA","body":"squares = llist(1, 4, 9, 16, 25)\n\nprint(ref(squares, 3)) ","output":"16"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p6","child":[{"body":"\n    Often we\n    \n\twalk down the whole linked list.\n      \n    To aid in this,\n    our Python environment\n    includes a primitive\n    predicate\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"is_none"},{"body":",\n    which tests whether its argument is the empty\n    linked list.\n    The\n    function","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":", which returns the number of items in a\n    linked list,\n    illustrates this typical pattern of use:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":13,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIANrgHYDmALgBYAUAlpbgLYDOAlAFwYi8gBOuSgFd+pELQAMIeoXqsA+qQD2pXAyZt2PPrt24irXCDQgA1MTJU6lAIb0iGlh3baMy7NlYgAvMSLylLRoADQgAMxhAKxhAOxuAA789KRBJBQ0tB5erkA","body":"def length(items):\n    return (0 if is_none(items)\n            else 1 + length(tail(items))) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":14,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIANrgHYDmALgBYAUAlpbgLYDOAlAFwYi8gBOuSgFd+pELQAMIeoXqsA+qQD2pXAyZt2PPrt24irXCDQgA1MTJU6lAIb0iGlh3baMy7NlYgAvMSLylLRoADQgAMxhAKxhAOxuAA789KRBJBQ0tB5erkA","body":"odds = llist(1, 3, 5, 7)\n\nprint(length(odds)) ","output":"4"},{"body":"\n    The ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":"function\n    implements a simple recursive plan. The reduction step is:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"UL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\tThe ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":" of any\n\tlinked list\n\tis 1 plus the\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":" of the\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"tail"},{"body":"\n\tof the\n\tlinked list.","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"body":"\n    This is applied successively until we reach the base case:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"UL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\tThe ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":" of the empty\n\tlinked list\n\tis 0.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"body":"\n    We could also compute ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":" in an iterative\n    style:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":15,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIANrgHYDmALgBYAUAlpbgLYDOAlAFwYi8gBOuSgFd+pELQAMIeoXqsA+qQD2pXAyZt2PPrt24irXCDQgA1MTJU6lAIb0iGlh3bacBSxRpOt3XXkISL2oFRlx+WlsAGhAAY2VhUkouHT0BIVFxWnjEyhk5RRU1SO00sr4DI09rUKYIuwcSmJyk8xNXVPSRMWqaWvCfVhjJN2VsbFYQAF5iInlKWjQYgGYYgFYYgHY3AAd+eiTaIOtaMYnXIA","body":"def length(items):\n    def length_iter(a, count):\n        return (count if is_none(a)\n                else length_iter(tail(a), count + 1))\n    return length_iter(items, 0) "}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p7","child":[{"body":"\n    Another conventional programming technique is to \n    \n\tconstruct an answer\n\tlinked list\n\tby adjoining elements to\n\tthe front of the linked list with\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"pair"},{"body":"\n\twhile walking down a linked list using\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"tail"},{"body":",\n      \n    as in the\n    function","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"append"},{"body":",\n\twhich takes two linked lists as arguments and\n\tcombines their elements to make a new linked list:\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":16,"eval":true,"prependLength":13,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIANrgHYDmALgBYAUAlpbgLYDOAlAFwYi8gBOuSgFd+pELQAMIeoXqsA+qQD2pXAyZt2PPrt24irXCDQgA1MTJU6lAIb0iGlh3bacBELYAOXstlpE8pRoADTEQYhcOryCImISgayUiDJyiipqAUFo2np5IAZGIF72-LTUuLb+icHsYd6+pP52DllJOWE1ka5YrACOwraCrCAAvMQ1tKEgACxhAJxhaABsYYgArG7K2Ngj40ST0wDMYethAOxuXvz0pJS017eUCgdBtA1+tP2Dw2Hbu652EA","body":"print(print_llist(append(squares, odds))) ","output":"llist(1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 1, 3, 5, 7)"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":17,"eval":true,"prependLength":13,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIANrgHYDmALgBYAUAlpbgLYDOAlAFwYi8gBOuSgFd+pELQAMIeoXqsA+qQD2pXAyZt2PPrt24irXCDQgA1MTJU6lAIb0iGlh3bacBELYAOXstlpE8pRoADTEQYhcOryCImISgayUiDJyiipqAUFo2np5IAZGIF72-LTUuLb+icHsYd6+pP52DllJOWE1ka5YrACOwraCrCAAvMQ1tKEgACxhAJxhaABsYYgArG7K2Ngj40ST0wDMYethAOxuXvz0pJS017eUCgdBtA1+tNu7Yf2Dw652EA","body":"print(print_llist(append(odds, squares))) ","output":"llist(1, 3, 5, 7, 1, 4, 9, 16, 25)"},{"body":"The function ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"append"},{"body":"\n    is also implemented using a recursive plan.\n    \n\tTo append\n\tlinked lists\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"list1"},{"body":" and\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"list2"},{"body":",\n\tdo the following:\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"UL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\tIf ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"list1"},{"body":" is the empty\n\t\n\t    linked list,\n\t  \n\tthen the\n      result is just ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"list2"},{"body":".\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\tOtherwise,\n\t\n\t    append the\n\t    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"tail"},{"body":"\n\t    of ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"list1"},{"body":" and \n\t    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"list2"},{"body":", and\n\t    adjoin\n\t    the\n\t    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"head"},{"body":"\n\t    of ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"list1"},{"body":"\n\t    to the result:\n\t  ","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":18,"eval":true,"prependLength":9,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIANrgHYDmALgBYAUAlpbgLYDOAlAFwYi8gBOuSgFd+pELQAMIeoXqsA+qQD2pXAyZt2PPrt24irXCDQgA1MTJU6lAIb0iGlh3baMrAI7Dbg1iAC8xETylLRoADQgACyRAJyRaABskYgArG7K2Nh+gUTBrKERIADMkamRAOxueIS2AA51ZNi0+ZRFrYhcOryCImISHTJyiipqLSFo2nrTIAZGIHX2-LTUuLbNrZOR9Y2kzXYO4wVbxCGdrlh1-PSkoVc3lAp5IbQ7TbSe3r6Rmdmu7EA","body":"def append(list1, list2):\n    return (list2 if is_none(list1)\n            else pair(head(list1), append(tail(list1), list2))) "}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.17","id":"#ex-2.17","child":[{"body":" \n    Define a\n    function","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"last_pair"},{"body":"\n    that returns the\n    \n\tlinked list\n      \n    that contains only the last element of a given\n    (nonempty)\n    \n\tlinked list:\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":19,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAdAGwIYDOALgPoAOeAlgE4hED2IARgKYgDmlAbiwHbMJiAVwAmfIljLVKvIgAopM0jhyVic-MXJVqG1esQBmADQgA7IlNoALAE5Th6wEoXToA","body":"print(print_llist(last_pair(llist(23, 72, 149, 34)))) ","output":"llist(34)"}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":20,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAdAGwIYDOALgPoAOeAlgE4hED2IARgKYgDmlAbiwHbMJiAVwAmfIljEAzEPmLkq1ABSUiLALYEAlAC4MIAyGosiQ6vxVrNISjMoESverxZKiVHJY3at+w--8WHAI2OVIKGjcPL00tOKwyakpeIiVE5NIcHHtUsIVIrJylRABmABoQAHZECrQAFgBOCpK6uLigA","body":"def last_pair(items):\n    return (items if is_none(tail(items))\n            else last_pair(tail(items))) "}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.18","id":"#ex-2.18","child":[{"body":"\n    Define a\n    function","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"reverse"},{"body":"\n    that takes a\n    linked list\n    as argument and\n    returns a\n    linked list\n    of the same elements in reverse order:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":21,"eval":true,"prependLength":8,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIATrgG65EDOuAFAJYAuuAtpQJQBcGIPIehJclVwB9RhXpNWAGmK5KAVwA2DTt14aSDBUQB2IGiUUqQdQnUojdAe121xrNuo0uXuJdTlDqYpkRoMAIZ0SpIs7NLOrtExsSAADsH+ABa4gdhhjrJGyqpsTpq42npeFD7i-g6UsgBytrhOGPFEdLoMNM2tDCJKShbtgmW0vf00aLIALLIAnLJoAGyyiACs+flAA","body":"print(print_llist(reverse(llist(1, 4, 9, 16, 25)))) ","output":"llist(25, 16, 9, 4, 1)"}],"solution":[{"body":"\n      Naive reverse (what is the run time?):\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":22,"eval":true,"prependLength":12,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIAhgA4m4B22AFADYCWAzgC5oA0IDLiAlAFwYQQkACdczAK4iKIOk2aIQ9QkwD6FAPYVcclmh6DhRo7lqNcIEkXojqAC1xEaXVjw6lyVas2u1drjhdeHgMcAlFcADdcEXNqemZcAFtGfkMhPEIxaNjcVQSY+MSUjjFGCVpmNONhMUlpWTKK5iUVRnUtHQKUgxq+4VNzCJzzfMTbH3o-btS2dP6FxaMrG3tHGhm3CPLKkN7a8SkZbJjRgtsZjgA5TtDM4dOu4tSBIzqj2RvtVqV2zW0islUvN+oMLB5KDQTrlvL5AT03CClsj+itbA4nPDZiAvrg9lgSCJ6BRmNRoXFaC5qOwQAAWDgAVg4AE4OGgAGwcRAMvZAA","body":"def reverse(items):\n    return (None if is_none(items)\n            else append(reverse(tail(items)),\n                                    pair(head(items), None))) "},{"body":"\n      A better version:\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":23,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIATrgG65EDOuAFAJYAuuAtpQJQBcGIPIehJclVwB9RhXpNWAGmK5KAVwA2DTt14aSDBUQB2IGiUUqQdQnUojdAe121xrNuo0uXuJdTlDqYpkRoMAIZ0SpIs7NLOrtExsSAADsH+ABa4gdhhjrJGyqpsTpq42npeFD7i-g6UsgBytrhOGPFEdLoMhmRltEpKFu1osgAssgCssgCcsmgAbLKII-lsQA","body":"def reverse(items):\n    def reverse_iter(items, result):\n        return (result if is_none(items)\n                else reverse_iter(tail(items),\n                                  pair(head(items), result)))\n    return reverse_iter(items, None) "}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.19","id":"#ex-2.19","child":[{"body":"\n      Consider the \n      \n      change-counting program of\n      section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"1.2.2","href":"/sicpjs/1.2.2"},{"body":".  It would be nice to be\n      able to easily change the currency used by the program, so that we could\n      compute the number of ways to change a British pound, for example.  As\n      the program is written, the knowledge of the currency is distributed\n      partly into the\n      function","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"first_denomination"},{"body":"\n      and partly into the\n      function","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"count_change"},{"body":"\n      (which knows\n      that there are five kinds of U.S. coins).\n      It would be nicer\n      to be able to supply a\n      linked list\n      of coins to be used for making change.\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p8","child":[{"body":"\n      We want to rewrite the\n      function","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"cc"},{"body":" so that its second argument\n      is a\n      linked list\n      of\n      the values of the coins to use rather than an integer specifying which\n      coins to use.  We could then have\n      linked lists\n      that defined each kind of\n      currency:\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":24,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYK4GcD6AxgPYCWAdriALwgA2dpuALgBQCsADADRLu9oeIfiDQBKHAGsiZSjXqMWrQUK69EQwbxGIBYoA","body":"us_coins = llist(50, 25, 10, 5, 1)\nuk_coins = llist(100, 50, 20, 10, 5, 2, 1) "},{"body":"\n      We could then call ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"cc"},{"body":" as follows:\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":25,"eval":true,"prependLength":13,"program":"chap=2&","body":"print(cc(100, us_coins)) ","output":"292"},{"body":"\n      To do this will require changing the program\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"cc"},{"body":" somewhat.  It will still have the same\n      form, but it will access its second argument differently, as follows:\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":26,"eval":true,"prependLength":7,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAdAMwJYBOAzgC4D6AJgKYB2A9gLZ40CGJedNANCFQB4BjKgAdy+YuWr0mrdp2wgWNCiHpkGdAlRAk6IAEbaA5ngButAwlIBXKSSzWiZAXWZEQAXhAAbb3lIAFACsAAw8iEE8aGEgkSBoAJQY1gDWzq407l6+-iQB0TGh4THRPHGIUUkY1DggAgIBLBrWNCQ8Lsxkpize1lRECQBcGCCjIFok1gQ0IPkgeLVNdC0knl4hI2NbW1TeRNoh84vNrSAAPCCHmqp06ppUAR00XT19A5vb27v7dQ1LKzx+EJRGRxKRKLRGMw2BwaI8Mi9ev0EgkQABqD6fLG-RonVYAWhAYMkkJkMM48M63SRA3aCOpbxRWGEBGYeXq+RCMUc6TcKKAA","body":"def cc(amount, coin_values):\n    return (1 if amount == 0\n            else 0 if amount < 0 or no_more(coin_values)\n            else cc(amount, except_first_denomination(coin_values)) +\n                 cc(amount - first_denomination(coin_values), coin_values)) "},{"body":"\n      Define the\n      functions","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"first_denomination"},{"body":",\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"except_first_denomination"},{"body":",\n\t\n      and\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"no_more"},{"body":"\n      in terms of primitive operations on\n      linked list\n      structures.  Does the order of\n      the\n      linked list","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"coin_values"},{"body":"\n      affect the answer produced by ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"cc"},{"body":"?\n      Why or why not?\n    ","tag":"#text"}]}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":27,"eval":true,"prependLength":13,"program":"chap=2&-fnMqhOBYiMRs57STZyHag6UjGIVIUpHQsPDBKV8kaypxqDRaE1fSI6+J61Iwsj0Gh9TWmyJYYQEZhklzk9FAgnMY5AA","body":"def first_denomination(coin_values):\n    return head(coin_values)\ndef except_first_denomination(coin_values):\n    return tail(coin_values)\ndef no_more(coin_values):\n    return is_none(coin_values) "},{"body":"\n      The order of the\n      linked list","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"coin_values"},{"body":"\n      does not affect the answer given by any correct solution of the problem,\n      because the given\n      linked list\n      represents an unordered collection of\n      denominations.\n    ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.20","id":"#ex-2.20","child":[{"body":"\n\tIn the presence of higher-order functions, it is not strictly necessary\n\tfor functions to have multiple parameters; one would\n\tsuffice. If we have a function such as\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"plus"},{"body":" that naturally requires two\n\targuments, we could write a variant of the function to which we pass\n\tthe arguments one at a time. An application of the variant to the\n\tfirst argument could return a function that we can then apply to the\n\tsecond argument, and so on. This practice—called\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"currying","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":" and named after the American mathematician and\n\tlogician\n\t\n\tHaskell Brooks Curry—is quite common in programming\n\tlanguages such as\n\t\n\tHaskell and\n\t\n\tOCaml. In Python, a curried\n\tversion of ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"plus"},{"body":" looks as follows.\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":28,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIADgDYCuAzgPoDGZATvQJa7YAUAHgJQBcGIAkPVwAXBgDsQJAIYBbAEbZpIODxAcQAahVYizcSLalKtBs1ZsAzFzYAWLlyA","body":"def plus_curried(x):\n    return lambda y: x + y "},{"body":"\n\tWrite a function ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"brooks"},{"body":" that\n\ttakes a curried function as first argument and as second argument a linked list\n\tof arguments to which the curried function is then applied, one by one,\n\tin the given order. For example, the following application of\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"brooks"},{"body":" should have the\n\tsame effect as\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"plus_curried(3)(4)"},{"body":":\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":29,"eval":true,"prependLength":6,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIADgDYCuAzgPoDGZATvQJa7YAUAHgJQBcGIAkPVwAXBgDsQJAIYBbAEbZpIODxAcQAahVZQ8+gHsDAawogRBkPNwgA7sxEjck+QhEALGxTF5xIrETMfmz6RqZspJS0DMysADRSJEzebADMCQAsXNlAA","body":"print(brooks(plus_curried, llist(3, 4))) ","output":"7"},{"body":"\n\tWhile we are at it, we might as well curry the function\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"brooks"},{"body":"! Write a function \n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"brooks_curried"},{"body":" that can be applied\n\tas follows:\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":30,"eval":true,"prependLength":6,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIADgDYCuAzgPoDGZATvQJa7YAUAHgJQBcGIAkPVwAXBgDsQJAIYBbAEbZpIODxAcQAahVZQ8+gHsDAa2p1GLbCBEGQ83CADuzESNyT5CEQAsHFMXjiIlhEzEFs+kamtAzMrGwkJEz+bKSUMRasADQgAMw5ACxcxUA","body":"print(brooks_curried(llist(plus_curried, 3, 4))) ","output":"7"},{"body":"\n\tWith this function ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"brooks_curried"},{"body":",\n\twhat are the results of evaluating the following two statements?\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":31,"eval":true,"prependLength":6,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIADgDYCuAzgPoDGZATvQJa7YAUAHgJQBcGIAkPVwAXBgDsQJAIYBbAEbZpIODxAcQAahVZQ8+gHsDAa2p1GLbCBEGQ83CADuzESNyT5CEQAsHFMXjiIlj6Rqa0DMysbCQkTP5soSZmkZYANPyCWdk5ArHxImyklBEWrGkgAMwVACxc9UA","body":"brooks_curried(llist(brooks_curried,\n                     llist(plus_curried, 3, 4))) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":32,"eval":true,"prependLength":6,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIADgDYCuAzgPoDGZATvQJa7YAUAHgJQBcGIAkPVwAXBgDsQJAIYBbAEbZpIODxAcQAahVZQ8+gHsDAa2p1GLbCBEGQ83CADuzESNyT5CEQAsHFMXjiIlj6Rqa0DMysbCQkTP5soSZmkZYANPyCWdk5ArHxIomGyREWrBm5lVWC+QmklKVR2GkgAMwtACxc3VxAA","body":"brooks_curried(llist(brooks_curried,\n                     llist(brooks_curried,\n                           llist(plus_curried, 3, 4)))) "}],"solution":[{"tag":"OL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":33,"eval":true,"prependLength":6,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIADgDYCuAzgPoDGZATvQJa7YAUAHgJQBcGIAkPVwAXBgDsQJAIYBbAEbZpIODxAcQAahVZQ8+gHsDAawogRBkPNwgA7sxEjck+QhEALGxTF5xIrHiE+kambPgANCBMTrIUvPyCwmL0kmFRhEzU4gbiuGzRuLFcCYKlgrgkFDbBJhRhbJ7S7AVFXJEi0kwk+TFxXMUYRMx+bDWhpJS0DMyskSQkmSJsAMyRACz9XEA","body":"def brooks(f, items):\n    return (f if is_none(items)\n            else brooks(f(head(items)), tail(items))) "}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":34,"eval":true,"prependLength":10,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIADgDYCuAzgPoDGZATvQJa7YAUAHgJQBcGIAkPVwAXBgDsQJAIYBbAEbZpIODxAcQAahVY8hefQD2hgNYU2+ADQgmI3LIq9+g4WPqSLNwk2rjD43DZbe0dnQXDBXBIKXBADYzMLNgALXGl2YIcuLmsRaSYSILss7KxQeNNqOkYWbBARQzjYgHdmETtJeQQRVJAKMTxxEV0COKNK2gZmViKQp3DXCTGE81T02azc-MLMxy4sImYhtgqzSZqZkhIfETZSSnPp7GsAZmsAFmyuIA","body":"def brooks_curried(items):\n    return brooks(head(items), tail(items)) "}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\t      The statement \n\t      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":35,"eval":true,"prependLength":11,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIADgDYCuAzgPoDGZATvQJa7YAUAHgJQBcGIAkPVwAXBgDsQJAIYBbAEbZpIODxAcQAahVY8hefQD2hgNYU2+ADQgmI3LIq9+g4WPqSLNwk2rjD43DZbe0dnQXDBXBIKXBADYzMLNgALXGl2YIcuLmsRaSYSILss7N0COKNTajpGFgzixz5w1wkKhPNU9KKQnJA8gu6SrCJmcRE2eKraBmZWNhISH3HJs2na1kswiO2dhaW2Uko12exrAGZrABZs7KA","body":"print(brooks_curried(llist(brooks_curried,\n                     llist(plus_curried, 3, 4)))) "},{"body":"\n\t      of course evaluates to 7, as does\n\t    ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":36,"eval":true,"prependLength":11,"program":"chap=2&","body":"print(brooks_curried(llist(brooks_curried,\n                     llist(brooks_curried,\n                           llist(plus_curried, 3, 4))))) "}]}]}]},{"tag":"SUBHEADING","id":"#h2","child":[{"body":"Mapping over linked lists","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p9","child":[{"body":"\n    One extremely useful operation is to apply some transformation to each\n    element in a\n    \n\tlinked list\n      \n    and generate the\n    \n\tlinked list\n      \n    of results. For instance, the\n    following\n    function\n    scales each number in a\n    \n\tlinked list\n      \n    by a given factor:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":37,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIAzgMYCGANrgPoUCWAdgNa7a11EAuAFHZ7gFsiAGhD4yJTgHsATgEoAXBhAqQM3JwCuMhiG4A5KQ1wg6hDtQZHcvfkLnLVTp7gpETABzJ0Z3ABa4ZNi2gkRyIABUYhLSMsKOzolJKqSUNPTMrOxc3JzeFCH2ouKSsnLlWB4yjDypVOyZbPQ5FM08aKKIogDMogAsogCscqJoAAzlQA","body":"def scale_linked_list(items, factor):\n    return (None if is_none(items)\n            else pair(head(items) * factor,\n                      scale_linked_list(tail(items), factor))) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":38,"eval":true,"prependLength":6,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIAzgMYCGANrgPoUCWAdgNa7a11EAuAFHZ7gFsiAGhD4yJTgHsATgEoAXBhAqQM3JwCuMhiG4A5KQ1wg6hDtQZHcvfkLnLVTp7gpETABzJ0Z3ABa4ZNi2gkRyIABUYhLSMsKOzolJKqSUNPTMrOxc3JzeFCH2ouKSsnLlWB4yjDypVOyZbPQ5FM08aKKIogDMogAsogCscqJoAAzlQA","body":"print(scale_linked_list(llist(1, 2, 3, 4, 5), 10)) ","output":"[10, [20, [30, [40, [50, None]]]]]"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p10","child":[{"body":"\n    We can abstract this general idea and capture it as a common pattern\n    expressed as a higher-order\n    function,\n    just as in section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"1.3","href":"/sicpjs/1.3"},{"body":".  The\n    higher-order\n    function\n    here is called ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":".\n    The function ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":"\n    takes as arguments a\n    function\n    of one argument and a\n    \n\tlinked list,\n      \n    and returns a\n    \n\tlinked list\n      \n    of the results produced by\n    applying the\n    function\n    to each element in the\n    linked list:","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":39,"eval":true,"prependLength":4,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIAhgEYDOAFAB4CUAXBiEyAE64AuAriwHYhUgAloQEA+ALwgADCFwAbMrhABafljyEAtkQAOFfJx4AaIe1yay9RszZdeICgDkA9jyXChZAPo9XuCoJmFjTWzGHM8oogOkSCLPqGFAAWuETYAUGWNEah4Xn5INp6BsYg7LFyGeZZNCEYOiyCPOwURRSkZCZycoJkLcpoUiYoAKwmA2jIAGwmaADstTRAA","body":"def map(fun, items):\n    return (None if is_none(items)\n            else pair(fun(head(items)),\n                      map(fun, tail(items)))) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":40,"eval":true,"prependLength":9,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIAhgEYDOAFAB4CUAXBiEyAE64AuAriwHYhUgAloQEA+ALwgADCFwAbMrhABafljyEAtkQAOFfJx4AaIe1yay9RszZdeICgDkA9jyXChZAPo9XuCoJmFjTWzGHM8oogOkSCLPqGFAAWuETYAUGWNEah4Xn5INp6BsYg7LFyGeZZNCEYOiyCPOwURRSkZCZycoJkLcpoUiYoAKwmA2jIAGwmaADstTRAA","body":"print(map(abs, llist(-10, 2.5, -11.6, 17))) ","output":"[10, [2.5, [11.6, [17, None]]]]"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":41,"eval":true,"prependLength":6,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIAtgIYAOAFPgK4B2ANCAJYAuuRAzgJQBcGIAkACdcLakNogKAOQD2tXM0JMOAfVrzcFVu279BBg7gA2HRWRJMhVOhQAWuEtm1tOXLvX2HvPgaUo0DCAslsYuuu7uWGRCTLQsFP4UxiREAEbYJCAAHjw5IABUOYzGxioJaIyIjADMjAAskUA","body":"print(map(lambda x: x * x, llist(1, 2, 3, 4))) ","output":"[1, [4, [9, [16, None]]]]"},{"body":"\n    Now we can give a new definition of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"scale_linked_list"},{"body":"\n    in terms of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":":\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":42,"eval":true,"prependLength":11,"program":"chap=2&","body":"def scale_linked_list(items, factor):\n    return map(lambda x: x * factor, items) "}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p11","child":[{"body":"The function ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":"\n    is an important construct, not only because it captures a common pattern,\n    but because it establishes a higher level of abstraction in dealing with\n    \n\tlinked lists.\n      \n    In the original definition of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"scale_linked_list"},{"body":",\n    the recursive structure of the program draws attention to the\n    element-by-element processing of the\n    \n\tlinked list.\n      \n    Defining\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"scale_linked_list"},{"body":"\n    in terms of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":"\n    suppresses that level of\n    detail and emphasizes that scaling transforms a\n    \n\tlinked list\n      \n    of elements to a\n    \n\tlinked list\n      \n    of results.  The difference between the two definitions is not that the\n    computer is performing a different process (it isn't) but that we\n    think about the process differently.  In effect,\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":"\n    helps establish an abstraction barrier\n    that isolates the implementation of\n    functions\n    that transform linked lists from the details of how the elements of the linked list are\n    extracted and combined.  Like the barriers shown in\n    \n\tfigure ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.1","href":"/sicpjs/2.1.2#fig-2.1"},{"body":",\n      \n    this abstraction gives us the flexibility to change the low-level details\n    of how sequences are implemented, while preserving the conceptual framework\n    of operations that transform sequences to sequences.\n    Section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.2.3","href":"/sicpjs/2.2.3"},{"body":" expands\n    on this use of sequences as a framework for organizing programs.\n  ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.21","id":"#ex-2.21","child":[{"body":"\n    The\n    function","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"square_linked_list"},{"body":"\n    takes a\n    linked list\n    of numbers as argument and returns a\n    linked list\n    of the squares of\n    those numbers.\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":43,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYA4CcCWAdgC4AUAzgI4CuAhrgKYD6ANkQNYMAmr+5ZLNv1JoANEnEBmcQBYAlAqA","body":"print(square_linked_list(llist(1, 2, 3, 4))) ","output":"[1, [4, [9, [16, None]]]]"},{"body":"\n    Here are two different definitions of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"square_linked_list"},{"body":".\n    Complete both of them by filling in the missing expressions:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":true,"eval":false,"body":"\ndef square_linked_list(items):\n    return (None if is_none(items)\n            else pair($\\langle{}$??$\\rangle$, $\\langle{}$??$\\rangle$))\n      "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":true,"eval":false,"body":"\ndef square_linked_list(items):\n    return map($\\langle{}$??$\\rangle$, $\\langle{}$??$\\rangle$)\n      "}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":44,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIAzgI4CuAhgE64AUAHgJQBcINALmVQHYj0gAqPljyFSlGgH0ANgEtuAa1zYZsou1qz2uALZEWGEEba5OPELQByAe264QswmsndbdLbv2HjPn7mlE9gAOFLJUtOLUdAAWuBTYmtp6jIwANN6+mVlGkVJyisqq6rTsodKJnikpWEFU8hq5uKoFKnLF0m0aaKlIPQDMPQAsVUA","body":"def square_linked_list(items):\n    return (None if is_none(items)\n            else pair(square(head(items)),\n                      square_linked_list(tail(items)))) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":45,"eval":true,"prependLength":8,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAYCYFMBmIAtgIYAOAFPgK4B2ANCAJYAuuRAzgJQBcGIAkACdcLakNogKAOQD2tXM0JMOAfVrzcFVu279BBg7gA2HRWRJMhVOhQAWuEtm1tOXLvX2HvPgaUo0DCAslsYuuu7uWHiEHACO1CQiFAAevMKi4pIpIABUICnRBCDxiSKqxky0ANa42BUqLOFufAYiYhLE5BSlSbiMOm5YZEJVTb3llTV1DRxNxpVzFGiMiIwAzIwALJFAA","body":"def square_linked_list(items):\n    return map(square, items) "}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.22","id":"#ex-2.22","child":[{"body":" \n    Louis Reasoner tries to rewrite the first\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"square_linked_list"},{"body":"function\n    of exercise ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.21","href":"/sicpjs/2.2.1#ex-2.21"},{"body":" so that it evolves an\n    iterative process:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":46,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=2&","body":"def square_linked_list(items):\n    def iter(things, answer):\n        return (answer if is_none(things)\n                else iter(tail(things),\n                          pair(square(head(things)),\n                               answer)))\n    return iter(items, None) "},{"body":"\n    Unfortunately, defining\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"square_linked_list"},{"body":"\n    this way produces the answer\n    linked list\n    in the reverse order of the one desired.\n    Why?\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p12","child":[{"body":"\n      Louis then tries to fix his bug by interchanging the arguments to\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"pair"},{"body":":","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":47,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=2&","body":"def square_linked_list(items):\n    def iter(things, answer):\n        return (answer if is_none(things)\n                else iter(tail(things),\n                          pair(answer,\n                               square(head(things)))))\n    return iter(items, None) "},{"body":"\n    This doesn't work either.  Explain.\n    ","tag":"#text"}]}],"solution":[{"tag":"OL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\t  The result\n\t  linked list\n\t  is reversed in the first program because the argument\n\t  linked list\n\t  is traversed in the given order, from first to last, but squares\n\t  are added successively to the front of the answer\n\t  linked list\n\t  via\n\t  ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"pair"},{"body":".\n\t  The last element of the\n\t  linked list\n\t  is the last one to be added to the answer\n\t  and thus ends up as the first element of the result\n\t  linked list.","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\t  The second program makes things worse! The result is not even a\n\t  linked list\n\t  any longer, because the elements occupy the tail position of the\n\t  result and not the head position.\n\t","tag":"#text"}]}]}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.23","id":"#ex-2.23","child":[{"body":"\n    The\n    function","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"for_each"},{"body":"\n    is similar to\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":"\n    It takes as arguments a\n    function\n    and a\n    linked list\n    of elements.  However, rather than forming a\n    linked list\n    of the\n    results,\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"for_each"},{"body":"\n    just applies the\n    function\n    to each of the elements in turn, from left to right. The values returned by\n    applying the\n    function\n    to the elements are not used\n    at all—","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"for_each"},{"body":"\n    is used with\n    functions\n    that perform an action, such as printing.  For example, \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":48,"eval":true,"prependLength":10,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAdAMwPYBOA+gKYCGAxgBYgAueIARiSAOYCWAbiQHZMIBnWgFcAJr1pZxOEPmLlqAChzCeAGhDtaJALYCAlAC4MIU5pnsBRHnh4lFW3QeNnXIAiREE+AOVskTMxIAGwESFzdTFR5FKnJRB209fX1AyLlSSiplVQ1aMnZgxKcUrAAHAnYeWmVCTKVgsh1GUTIQAA9DEAqqmvb9DWDgyxqAVgB2DQBmRDQNAA55lP0gA","body":"print(for_each(lambda x: print(x), llist(57, 321, 88))) ","output":"57\n321\n88"},{"body":"\n    The value returned by the call to\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"for_each"},{"body":"\n    (not illustrated above) can be something arbitrary, such as true.  Give an\n    implementation of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"for_each"},{"body":".","tag":"#text"}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":49,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhQRgFAdAMwPYBOA+gKYCGAxgBYgAueIARiSAOYCWAbiQHZMIBnWgFcAJr1pZxOEPmLlqAChzCeAGhDtaJALYCAlAC4MIU5pnsBRHnh4lFW3QeNnXIAiREE+AOVskTMxIAGwESFzdTFR5FKnJRB209fX1AyLlSSiplVQ1aMnZgxKcUrAAHAnYeWmVCTKVgsh1GUTIQAA9DEAqqmvb9DWDgyxqAVgB2DQBmRDQNAA55lP0gA","body":"def for_each(fun, items):\n    if is_none(items):\n        return None\n    else:\n        fun(head(items))\n        for_each(fun, tail(items)) "}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-1","count":1,"href":"/sicpjs/2.2.1#footnote-link-1","child":[{"body":"In this book, we use\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"linked list","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":"\n    to mean a chain of\n    pairs terminated by the end-of-linked-list marker.\n    In contrast, the term\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"linked-list structure","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":"\n    refers to any data structure made out of pairs, \n    not just to\n    linked lists.","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-2","count":2,"href":"/sicpjs/2.2.1#footnote-link-2","child":[{"body":"The value\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"None"},{"body":" is used in Python for\n\tvarious purposes, as we shall see in chapter ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"3","href":"/sicpjs/3"},{"body":".","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-3","count":3,"href":"/sicpjs/2.2.1#footnote-link-3","child":[{"body":"Our Python environment provides\n      a primitive function\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"print_llist"},{"body":"\n      that works like the primitive function\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"print"},{"body":", except that\n      it uses linked-list notation instead of box notation.\n    ","tag":"#text"}]}]